1
00:00:01,960 --> 00:00:03,970
DRAKE CARLSTON: Awesome.

2
00:00:03,970 --> 00:00:04,870
Welcome, guys.

3
00:00:04,870 --> 00:00:07,030
We're reviewing the
Tableau Concepts

4
00:00:07,030 --> 00:00:11,560
section of the survival guide.

5
00:00:11,560 --> 00:00:13,600
Super helpful if you
guys want to prepare

6
00:00:13,600 --> 00:00:16,390
for the final or
the certification.

7
00:00:19,380 --> 00:00:21,720
Let's start.

8
00:00:21,720 --> 00:00:24,240
In Tableau, we have
dimensions and measures.

9
00:00:24,240 --> 00:00:26,910
And if you're like me,
these are the first things

10
00:00:26,910 --> 00:00:31,050
that come to mind when
I think of those words.

11
00:00:31,050 --> 00:00:34,290
But that's not what
we're dealing with.

12
00:00:34,290 --> 00:00:36,575
We're doing something
cooler, data.

13
00:00:39,850 --> 00:00:41,320
I pulled this from--

14
00:00:41,320 --> 00:00:45,740
everything I'm doing is coming
from the Tableau Help website,

15
00:00:45,740 --> 00:00:48,790
which is a super helpful
resource for anything

16
00:00:48,790 --> 00:00:49,720
Tableau related.

17
00:00:49,720 --> 00:00:53,470
There's a ton of
documentation all by Tableau.

18
00:00:53,470 --> 00:00:54,670
Super helpful.

19
00:00:54,670 --> 00:00:56,180
This is straight from that.

20
00:00:56,180 --> 00:00:59,410
So before we get into
dimensions and measures,

21
00:00:59,410 --> 00:01:04,930
we need to understand that
Tableau identifies each field

22
00:01:04,930 --> 00:01:06,650
as a dimension or measure.

23
00:01:06,650 --> 00:01:12,070
So every field comes from a
column in your data source.

24
00:01:12,070 --> 00:01:15,100
And you might have
covered this in class,

25
00:01:15,100 --> 00:01:18,700
but that's why every year--

26
00:01:18,700 --> 00:01:20,240
if you're working
on your project

27
00:01:20,240 --> 00:01:22,960
and you add some data
source, and there

28
00:01:22,960 --> 00:01:25,720
are like a million
things here and you

29
00:01:25,720 --> 00:01:27,700
have to scroll
through them, that's

30
00:01:27,700 --> 00:01:32,260
an example of wide data, which
is less optimized for Tableau.

31
00:01:32,260 --> 00:01:36,710
So all of those columns are
being turned into fields.

32
00:01:36,710 --> 00:01:38,780
And those fields
are either going

33
00:01:38,780 --> 00:01:41,820
to be dimensions or measures.

34
00:01:41,820 --> 00:01:48,060
So this is the main difference
between dimensions and measures.

35
00:01:48,060 --> 00:01:54,250
Dimensions are qualitative, the
characteristics of the data,

36
00:01:54,250 --> 00:01:59,430
while measures are
quantitative, like numbers.

37
00:01:59,430 --> 00:02:04,010
So the way I remember it,
qualitative, qualities,

38
00:02:04,010 --> 00:02:05,795
quantitative, quantity.

39
00:02:08,530 --> 00:02:11,470
Yeah, that's really it.

40
00:02:11,470 --> 00:02:19,300
So specifically, dimensions can
be any of these things or more.

41
00:02:19,300 --> 00:02:23,650
Here are some examples
from the superstore data

42
00:02:23,650 --> 00:02:26,755
set that's available on the
desktop version of Tableau.

43
00:02:31,850 --> 00:02:37,820
So they categorize the data,
and then same with measures.

44
00:02:37,820 --> 00:02:40,190
What's unique about
measures, though,

45
00:02:40,190 --> 00:02:45,250
is they have aggregations
applied to them by default.

46
00:02:45,250 --> 00:02:48,910
So measures, they're numbers.

47
00:02:48,910 --> 00:02:55,600
So when we bring something out
into a visualization by default

48
00:02:55,600 --> 00:02:58,460
Tableau, we want to do
something to those numbers,

49
00:02:58,460 --> 00:03:03,270
so it's, I guess, smaller.

50
00:03:03,270 --> 00:03:07,390
We will cover that more.

51
00:03:07,390 --> 00:03:10,150
You might be asked
something like this,

52
00:03:10,150 --> 00:03:13,150
if something has an
aggregation applied to it,

53
00:03:13,150 --> 00:03:14,725
it's most likely a measure.

54
00:03:17,710 --> 00:03:20,560
Moving on.

55
00:03:20,560 --> 00:03:23,620
Did any of you guys talk
about this in class?

56
00:03:23,620 --> 00:03:26,980
I'm not sure if this is
something we covered in class.

57
00:03:26,980 --> 00:03:29,350
But like I mentioned
before, measures

58
00:03:29,350 --> 00:03:32,480
have these aggregations
applied to them.

59
00:03:32,480 --> 00:03:36,850
So there's actually a way
to turn that off in Tableau.

60
00:03:41,060 --> 00:03:43,180
This is a classic example.

61
00:03:43,180 --> 00:03:45,540
So we bring out--

62
00:03:45,540 --> 00:03:48,450
let's say we want to look at the
relationship between discount

63
00:03:48,450 --> 00:03:51,390
and profit.

64
00:03:51,390 --> 00:03:54,470
So by default, it applies
the sum aggregation,

65
00:03:54,470 --> 00:03:57,500
so there's just one point.

66
00:03:57,500 --> 00:04:01,940
There are two ways we can
turn that aggregation off.

67
00:04:01,940 --> 00:04:05,450
One is under analysis.

68
00:04:05,450 --> 00:04:08,720
This is selected, aggregate
measures is selected by default.

69
00:04:08,720 --> 00:04:10,820
If we turn that off--

70
00:04:10,820 --> 00:04:14,570
let's flip the axis so
it's more meaningful--

71
00:04:14,570 --> 00:04:18,470
if we turn that off, it
takes all those points

72
00:04:18,470 --> 00:04:22,940
and breaks them out so
they're not aggregated.

73
00:04:22,940 --> 00:04:29,430
Another way to do that
would be to come in here

74
00:04:29,430 --> 00:04:32,190
and select dimension.

75
00:04:32,190 --> 00:04:34,470
And that does the same thing.

76
00:04:34,470 --> 00:04:39,600
But basically, a dimension
cannot have this aggregation

77
00:04:39,600 --> 00:04:40,260
applied to it.

78
00:04:43,290 --> 00:04:45,240
So there you go.

79
00:04:45,240 --> 00:04:48,900
That's aggregation.

80
00:04:48,900 --> 00:04:51,150
This is another screenshot
from Tableau Help.

81
00:04:51,150 --> 00:04:52,900
Super helpful.

82
00:04:52,900 --> 00:04:55,860
OK, so that's
dimensions and measures.

83
00:04:55,860 --> 00:04:57,790
Now we have discrete
or continuous.

84
00:05:00,970 --> 00:05:01,810
This is it.

85
00:05:01,810 --> 00:05:07,600
So continuous means it's green
and forming an unbroken whole.

86
00:05:07,600 --> 00:05:10,780
Discrete is blue with
individual and distinct.

87
00:05:10,780 --> 00:05:14,320
Does this make sense?

88
00:05:14,320 --> 00:05:16,550
When it's written like
this, it's easy to see,

89
00:05:16,550 --> 00:05:17,810
but I always mix them up.

90
00:05:17,810 --> 00:05:23,510
So continuous, like
if you're running

91
00:05:23,510 --> 00:05:26,630
and you run a mile continuously,
there are no breaks.

92
00:05:26,630 --> 00:05:30,110
But if you run a
discrete mile, which

93
00:05:30,110 --> 00:05:32,600
is not something you
would say in English,

94
00:05:32,600 --> 00:05:34,100
but there are these--

95
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:35,150
it's broken up.

96
00:05:42,020 --> 00:05:46,430
One thing we want you
to understand is--

97
00:05:46,430 --> 00:05:47,210
where is it?

98
00:05:51,050 --> 00:05:55,160
We want you to understand how
discrete and continuous fields

99
00:05:55,160 --> 00:05:58,220
are displayed.

100
00:05:58,220 --> 00:06:00,920
Hey, Kauri, welcome in.

101
00:06:00,920 --> 00:06:06,200
So by default, when you just
bring out a discrete field,

102
00:06:06,200 --> 00:06:10,200
it's going to create a header.

103
00:06:10,200 --> 00:06:13,275
And then with a continuous,
it's going to create an axis.

104
00:06:17,020 --> 00:06:18,040
I'll show you.

105
00:06:18,040 --> 00:06:20,590
That might be more helpful.

106
00:06:20,590 --> 00:06:23,980
Let's just make a new one.

107
00:06:23,980 --> 00:06:27,370
It's hard, just
based on that snip.

108
00:06:27,370 --> 00:06:29,230
Here is a continuous field.

109
00:06:29,230 --> 00:06:33,120
We bring it out, and
it creates an axis.

110
00:06:33,120 --> 00:06:36,720
Meanwhile, if we
look at segment here,

111
00:06:36,720 --> 00:06:39,450
it's going to
create this header.

112
00:06:39,450 --> 00:06:44,130
And if we do it the other
way around, use the header

113
00:06:44,130 --> 00:06:50,250
segment first, there you go.

114
00:06:50,250 --> 00:06:53,590
Know that, that's on this.

115
00:06:53,590 --> 00:06:57,975
So moving on.

116
00:06:57,975 --> 00:06:59,550
There are four themes.

117
00:07:02,640 --> 00:07:06,030
There are four things you want
to consider, dimension, measure,

118
00:07:06,030 --> 00:07:08,670
discrete, continuous.

119
00:07:08,670 --> 00:07:14,990
And a pill will fall into
one of these categories.

120
00:07:14,990 --> 00:07:18,080
This is super helpful to know.

121
00:07:18,080 --> 00:07:24,170
So the trick that I use to
remember is that anything can be

122
00:07:24,170 --> 00:07:29,830
anything except a continuous
dimension cannot have a Boolean

123
00:07:29,830 --> 00:07:30,850
or string value.

124
00:07:33,410 --> 00:07:35,300
And that makes sense.

125
00:07:35,300 --> 00:07:37,460
If something is a
Boolean, like true, false,

126
00:07:37,460 --> 00:07:40,460
it can't be continuous.

127
00:07:40,460 --> 00:07:42,445
And same with other words.

128
00:07:47,200 --> 00:07:51,374
I made some examples of these.

129
00:07:51,374 --> 00:07:55,680
These are not super
interpretable.

130
00:07:55,680 --> 00:07:58,020
Well, some of them are.

131
00:07:58,020 --> 00:08:01,680
You would never have a discrete
measure and a discrete dimension

132
00:08:01,680 --> 00:08:04,170
compared like
this, but this just

133
00:08:04,170 --> 00:08:08,260
helps you visualize
that any pill can

134
00:08:08,260 --> 00:08:10,440
be one of these four things.

135
00:08:10,440 --> 00:08:12,850
And this is what
they would look like.

136
00:08:12,850 --> 00:08:16,530
So with a discrete dimension
and discrete measure,

137
00:08:16,530 --> 00:08:20,790
you've got whatever this is.

138
00:08:20,790 --> 00:08:26,820
But notice, sum of
profit as a discrete pill

139
00:08:26,820 --> 00:08:31,050
is broken out into
these four sections.

140
00:08:31,050 --> 00:08:35,519
And there's only a match
on every single year value.

141
00:08:39,240 --> 00:08:39,900
Moving on.

142
00:08:39,900 --> 00:08:41,549
Some of these make more sense.

143
00:08:41,549 --> 00:08:46,170
So same here, notice we
have this sum of profit,

144
00:08:46,170 --> 00:08:52,210
which is numbers, but we
have them as discrete fields.

145
00:08:52,210 --> 00:08:56,640
So it's a discrete measure
with this continuous value--

146
00:08:56,640 --> 00:08:58,630
with this continuous
dimension value.

147
00:08:58,630 --> 00:09:03,300
So if we expand this
and get more detail,

148
00:09:03,300 --> 00:09:05,730
you can kind of see
this continuous line.

149
00:09:05,730 --> 00:09:08,100
Those two don't make
very much sense.

150
00:09:08,100 --> 00:09:13,810
Next, we have a discrete
dimension and a continuous year.

151
00:09:13,810 --> 00:09:20,130
So notice it's continuous
measure, so we have a line,

152
00:09:20,130 --> 00:09:24,250
but we have this
discrete broken up year.

153
00:09:24,250 --> 00:09:28,050
So when we expand
this, this line,

154
00:09:28,050 --> 00:09:33,525
it's only continuous within each
quarter, and same for month.

155
00:09:37,510 --> 00:09:41,740
And then this is an actually
interpretable graph.

156
00:09:45,890 --> 00:09:47,032
This should be green.

157
00:09:50,410 --> 00:09:50,980
There we go.

158
00:09:50,980 --> 00:09:56,700
As we increase this
level of detail

159
00:09:56,700 --> 00:10:02,240
on the dimension,
the date dimension,

160
00:10:02,240 --> 00:10:04,390
we have this continuous line.

161
00:10:04,390 --> 00:10:08,420
Then this is just a combination,
so you can see all of them

162
00:10:08,420 --> 00:10:09,290
at the same time.

163
00:10:12,410 --> 00:10:15,360
Awesome.

164
00:10:15,360 --> 00:10:17,520
That's mostly it.

165
00:10:17,520 --> 00:10:21,530
The main takeaway
here, in general, I

166
00:10:21,530 --> 00:10:25,440
think this is a good rule,
and this is how I remember.

167
00:10:25,440 --> 00:10:28,650
Blue pills break green
pills into smaller pieces.

168
00:10:33,200 --> 00:10:37,040
Here, we have an
aggregated measure.

169
00:10:37,040 --> 00:10:39,670
It is just one number, one bar.

170
00:10:39,670 --> 00:10:41,425
If you bring--

171
00:10:41,425 --> 00:10:43,780
I forget what I
had-- segment out,

172
00:10:43,780 --> 00:10:47,020
it divides that
into smaller chunks

173
00:10:47,020 --> 00:10:48,265
and gives you more detail.

174
00:10:52,710 --> 00:10:58,950
That's pretty much all I have
to present that's meaningful.

175
00:10:58,950 --> 00:11:03,390
Notice in here, there are these
videos for Tableau Concepts.

176
00:11:03,390 --> 00:11:05,430
There are two videos.

177
00:11:05,430 --> 00:11:07,230
Kaitlin Olson made them.

178
00:11:07,230 --> 00:11:09,690
So I don't want to steal
the glory from her,

179
00:11:09,690 --> 00:11:13,650
but these are helpful,
especially this one,

180
00:11:13,650 --> 00:11:19,300
if you want to review more of
what different date values look

181
00:11:19,300 --> 00:11:24,400
like, whether they're
discrete or continuous.

182
00:11:24,400 --> 00:11:29,620
Also, these slides
will be available.

183
00:11:29,620 --> 00:11:32,650
Watch this video.

184
00:11:32,650 --> 00:11:34,300
Paul does a really good job.

185
00:11:34,300 --> 00:11:36,430
It's like six
minutes, but he covers

186
00:11:36,430 --> 00:11:41,800
everything I did super fast
and probably with more detail.

187
00:11:41,800 --> 00:11:43,120
And then this is what I use.

188
00:11:43,120 --> 00:11:44,740
This is Tableau.

189
00:11:44,740 --> 00:11:49,080
Literally, anything
